Dear Ladies and Gentlemen, <br>
<br>
At the release of Shadows of Luclin, the paladin spell Thunder of Karana was seriously unbalanced. Three or four paladins could relatively easily shut down all special effects of an uber mob or high level encounter by chain casting Thunder of Karana. Examples are 12 people slaying Sontalek or Lady Vox/Gorenaire.A fight that was reduced to the difficult of fighting a giant in Kael. Action had to be taken quickly and the spell was changed to a mana sieve spell. <br>
<br>
Discussion of a Workable Silencing Spell<br>
---------------------------------------<br>
<br>
The paladin community started discussing a fair replacement spell that fulfilled the original intent of the spell: to give paladins a specific raid role by granting them the ability to counter gate and complete heal spells of high end encounters and mobs. Dragon AoE's, breath weapons and special procs should not be affected by the silence. <br>
<br>
We discussed different options and we came to the conclusion that only a spell that was chaincastable by several paladins would fulfill the hopes of us paladins. We were hoping that a raid force desired to have more than just one paladin for Divine Strength on a raid. A chaincastable spell would accomplish that. Secondarily, silencing a dragon for only one spell duration would only mean that a dragon would gate or complete heal after the six seconds passed. Only a chainable version of a silence spell would make a noticable difference, but not trivialize the encounter.<br>
<br>
The original spell statistics for mana, duration and recast time were perfect. Thunder of Karana would have found good but not unbalancing use in raid scenarios as well as regular fights in places like Sebilis or Karnor's Castle. The resist levels were well balanced for single or chained use of the spell. The only thing 'wrong' with it is the component that prohibited the mob from doing special attacks like AoE's, Breaths and procs. (Dragon roar comes to mind). <br>
<br>
Implementation of a Balanced Working Silence Spell<br>
---------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
From there we discussed different implementations that would allow AoE breath weapons and procs to continue, but regular spells like Complete Heal and Gate to be silenced. We understand these special attacks of dragons are coded as spells similar to any other spell.<br>
<br>
In the selection of the approach we tried to find a method that would not require extensive programming, reviewing each mob's spell selection or time intensive flagging of mobs and spells that can be silenced. Only an approach that could globally be applied and does not require review of all mobs in Everquest would be feasable. There is a general concern in the paladin community that any complex implementation would be discussed but due to time and cost issues never implemented. <br>
<br>
There are a few approaches that could be used to restrict the repertoire of a silenced mob's spells to only AoE or proc weapons without excessive implementation cost. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    a)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->Restrict the spell list of a silenced dragon to only spells that:<br>
<br>
o have a cast time of less than 1 second <br>
o have zero mana cost<br>
<br>
In other words, Thunder of Karana would only silence spells that have a casting time greater than 1 second (AE's and procs are instant), and cost mana (So skills like Lay hands, Harm touch, and death touch will still be able to be cast).<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    b)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Lower the channeling skill of a dragon by 95% when the dragon is silenced. This would similarily to restricting the spell selection list allow fast casting AoE weapons and procs to succeed but gates and complete heals to be interrupted.<br>
<br>
<br>
We believe that the suggested implementation options would fulfill the great initial thought of the Thunder of Karana spell and give Paladins a specific and accumulative raid role they lack, need and want so badly. The risk of introducing an unbalancing spell with this implementation is low, so is the development cost.<br>
<br>
Please consider the above thoughts. Feel free to contact me or any member of the Paladin of Norrath community for further information.<br>
